<aside class="author-card">
  <h3 class="author-card-heading">About the Author</h3>
  <hr class="author-rule pink" />
  <p>Jason Alan Terry is a dad, an engineer, and an entrepreneur.</p>
  <hr class="author-rule purple" />
  <p>He is the co-founder of Antidote Games, a tabletop game company running the Antidote Labs program, a community for aspiring game designers learning to develop their craft and bring their games to market. He has spent years building software across a wide range of domains, languages, and frameworks, accumulating the kind of broad, practical engineering knowledge that comes from having built a lot of things and having understood all of them.</p>
  <hr class="author-rule yellow" />
  <p>His current work includes an AI-powered product for children designed with child safety and parental transparency as foundational requirements, not afterthoughts. The belief that the humans using a system should understand and control what it does, and that building without that understanding is a form of negligence, runs through everything he builds.</p>
  <hr class="author-rule pink" />
  <p>E² is not something he invented in theory. It is how he works. Every project in this paper was built with it. Including this paper.</p>
